08235nam a22013095i 9783110245486DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20102010gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2010011924  a(OCoLC)979632844  a97831102454867 a10.1515/97831102454862doi  a(DE-B1597)39570  a(OCoLC)676698348  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aPN56.L3bL39 2010 4aPN56.L3bL39 2010eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809a809.93354a809/.9335400aLaughter in the Middle Ages and Early Modern Times :bEpistemology of a Fundamental Human Behavior, its Meaning, and Consequences /ced. by Albrecht Classen. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (853 p.) :bNum. figs.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFundamentals of Medieval and Early Modern Culture ,x1864-3396 ;v50 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite popular opinions of the ‘dark Middle Ages’ and a ‘gloomy early modern age,’ many people laughed, smiled, giggled, chuckled, entertained and ridiculed each other. This volume demonstrates how important laughter had been at times and how diverse the situations proved to be in which people laughed, and this from late antiquity to the eighteenth century. The contributions examine a wide gamut of significant cases of laughter in literary texts, historical documents, and art works where laughter determined the relationship among people. In fact, laughter emerges as a kaleidoscopic phenomenon reflecting divine joy, bitter hatred and contempt, satirical perspectives and parodic intentions. In some examples protagonists laughed out of sheer happiness and delight, in others because they felt anxiety and insecurity. It is much more difficult to detect premodern sculptures of laughing figures, but they also existed. Laughter reflected a variety of concerns, interests, and intentions, and the collective approach in this 